.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">
Our study showed that the chromosome number of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hub - Mor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Centaurea drabifolioides" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="drabifolioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">Centaurea drabifolioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hub.-Mor. is 2n = 18 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Somatic chromosomes, karyotype and idiogram of Centaurea ziganensis (a-c); Centaurea drabifolioides (d-f). Arrow indicates satellite. Scale bars = 5 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.53.5250.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/47598" pageId="3" pageNumber="30">2d</figureCitation>
). The shortest chromosome length is 1.51 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, the longest is 2.77 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, and the haploid chromosome length is 18.64 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. The karyotype formula of this taxon consists of 10 median pairs and 8 submedian pairs. Satellites were usually seen on the 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="31" start="start">short</pageBreakToken>
arms of shortest sub-metacentric chromosomes. As for karyotype asymmetry, the karyotype of this species is classified according to the symmetry classes of Stebbins as 3A. Intrachromosomal asymmetry (MCA) is 22.71 and the interchromosomal asymmetry index (CVCL) is 17.95. The karyogram is given in Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Somatic chromosomes, karyotype and idiogram of Centaurea ziganensis (a-c); Centaurea drabifolioides (d-f). Arrow indicates satellite. Scale bars = 5 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.53.5250.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/47598" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">2e</figureCitation>
, and ideogram was drawn based on the centromeric index (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Somatic chromosomes, karyotype and idiogram of Centaurea ziganensis (a-c); Centaurea drabifolioides (d-f). Arrow indicates satellite. Scale bars = 5 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.53.5250.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/47598" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">2f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="31" type="sem observations">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="31">SEM observations.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Seed surface pattern of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yuezb., M. Bona &amp; I. Genc" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Centaurea ziganensis" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ziganensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Centaurea ziganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is ruminate. Testa cells are regularly arranged, elongated parallel with the seed surface and the cells are apparently imbricate. The cell boundaries are thin and have smooth structure, and the boundaries raised above cell centre (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron micrographs of achene surface. (a-c) Centaurea ziganensis. (d-f) Centaurea drabifolioides." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.53.5250.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/47599" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">3a-c</figureCitation>
). Even seed surface pattern and testa cell arrangement of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hub - Mor" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Centaurea drabifolioides" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="drabifolioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Centaurea drabifolioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yuezb., M. Bona &amp; I. Genc" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Centaurea ziganensis" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ziganensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Centaurea ziganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the cell centres raised above the boundaries and testa cells are not apparently imbricate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Scanning electron micrographs of achene surface. (a-c) Centaurea ziganensis. (d-f) Centaurea drabifolioides." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.53.5250.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/47599" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">3d-f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
